The '''Dornier Do P''' was a German four-engined [[heavy bomber]] manufactured by [[Dornier Flugzeugwerke]] in the 1930s. It was built as part of [[German re-armament|the secret rearmament]] of Germany in opposition of the [[Treaty of Versailles]].
==Design and development== Construction of the Do P began in July 1929, and its first flight took place on March 31, 1930. The aircraft was tested in such places as [[Lipetsk]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Schliephake|first=Hanfried|title=The birth of the Luftwaffe|year=1971|publisher=Regnery|page=20}}</ref> The Do P was a monoplane constructed mainly of metal, but covered in some places by [[Aircraft fabric covering|fabric]]. The aircraft was powered by four nine-cylinder [[Bristol Jupiter|Siemens Jupiter]] VI, each with 530 horsepower. The aircraft had a crew of six. It was eventually developed into the [[Dornier Do 11]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wragg|first=David W.|title=The offensive weapon: the strategy of bombing|year=1986|publisher=R. Hale|isbn=978-0-7090-2787-4|page=56}}</ref>
